-- t11. Mommy in the Field: Raising Children and Breeding Plants -- tPart V. What Is the Field, Anyway? Mothers Redefining Field Methodologies -- tIntroduction -- t12. Entangled Knowledge: On the Labor of Mothering and Anthropological Fieldwork -- t13. “Manman, Poukisa Y’ap Rele M Blan?” (Mama, Why Are They Calling Me a White?): Research and Mothering in Haiti -- t14. Birthing the Social Scientist as Mother -- t15. Two Notes on Bringing Children Other Than Your Own in the Field -- tPart VI. Practical Solutions to Complex Problems: Because Mothers Can Do Anything! -- tIntroduction -- t16. “I Don’t Know How You Do It!”: Countering a Narrative that Presumes that Researching and Mothering Are Incompatible -- t17. Ethnographic Research in Africa: The Hidden Costs of Conducting Fieldwork for Mothers with Children -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe heated national conversation about gender equality and women in the workforce is something that women in academia have been concerned with and writing about for at least a decade. Overall, the conversation has focused on identifying how women in general and mothers in particular fair in the academy as a whole, as well as offering tips on how to maximize success. Aside from a long-standing field-specific debate in anthropology, rare are the volumes focusing on the particulars of motherhood’s impacts on how scientific research is conducted, particularly when it comes to field research. Mothering from the Field offers both a mosaic of perspectives from current women scientists’ experiences of conducting field research across a variety of sub-disciplines while raising children, and an analytical framework to understand how we can redefine methodological and theoretical contributions based on mothers’ experiences in order not just to promote healthier, more inclusive, nurturing, and supportive environments in physical, life, and social sciences, but also to revolutionize how we conceptualize research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aResearchxMethodology. 0aSciencexFieldwork. 0aSocial sciencesxFieldwork. 0aWomen college teachers. 0aWomen scientists. 0aWomen social scientists. 0aWork and family. 0aWorking mothers. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCamp, Stacey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamp, Stacey.1 aCampbell, Kimberly Garland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Lydia Zacher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDixon, Lydia Zacher.1 aEricsson, Aprille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEricsson, Aprille.1 aEricsson, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEricsson, Pierre.1 aEricsson-Provine, Dawn.1 aGarland-Campbell, Kimberly.1 aGuthrie, Deirdre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuthrie, Deirdre.1 aHardgrove, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardgrove, Anne.1 aKarram, Joanne Florence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarram, Joanne Florence.1 aKelman, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelman, Sarah.1 aMarco, Lindsey Alyssa.1 aMarco, Lindsey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuhammad, Bahiyyah M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMuhammad, Bahiyyah Miallah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuhammad, Muntaquim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuhammad, Muntaquim.1 aNeuilly, M